fix(codegen): Implement loop-escaping variable hoisting (Refs DEPYLER-0762)

Python has function-level scoping, so variables assigned inside for/while
loops are visible after the loop. Rust has block-level scoping, which caused
E0425 "cannot find value" errors when transpiling such patterns.

This fix adds variable hoisting for for/while loops:
- Added collect_loop_escaping_variables() to detect variables assigned in loops
  that are used after the loop
- Added collect_all_assigned_variables() to recursively find all assignments
- Added is_var_used_in_remaining_stmts() and is_var_used_in_expr_any() helpers
- Hoisted variables are declared with Default::default() to avoid E0381
  "possibly-uninitialized" errors

Example transformation:
  Python:                           Rust (before):
  for i in range(10):              for i in 0..10 {
      if i > 5:                        if i > 5 {
          result = i                       let result = i;  // scoped!
          break                            break;
  return result  # OK                  }
                                    }
                                    result  // E0425: not found

  Rust (after):
  let mut result = Default::default();  // hoisted!
  for i in 0..10 {
      if i > 5 {
          result = i;
          break;
      }
  }
  result  // OK

Test: 811 tests pass, repro file compiles successfully.

